\begin_layout Subsection
A simple model
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is observed that if a temperature gradient is applied (to what? a metal)
 there is a flow of current.
 This may be stated as 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
E=Q\nabla T
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $Q\equiv\text{Thermopower}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 is the temperature (a function of position), and 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 is the electric field created by the temperature gradient.
 This effect is known as the seeback effect.
 
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
It maybe stated for completeness that there's a peltier effect, which creates
 a temperature gradient upon application of a potential difference.
 However this is not considered here.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let us develop the idea under the assumptions of the Drude model.
 Consider a 1 dimensional case.
 Since by assumption, in the Drude model, the velocity of electrons depends
 on the local temperature, we may write an expression for the velocity of
 electrons due to the temperature gradient as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
v_{Q}=\frac{1}{2}[v(x-v\tau)-v(x+v\tau)]=-\tau\frac{dv}{dx}=-\tau\frac{d}{dx}\left(\frac{v^{2}}{2}\right)
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

 is the local average velocity of the particle and 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 is the average time between collisions; We can generalize this readily
 to the 3d case by putting 
\begin_inset Formula $v^{2}\rightarrow v_{x}^{2}$
\end_inset

 and nothing that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
<v_{i}^{2}>=\frac{1}{3}v^{2};\, i\in\{x,y,z\}
\]

\end_inset

so that we have (using the 3d generalization of 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{dv^{2}}{dx}=\frac{dv^{2}}{dT}\frac{dT}{dx}$
\end_inset

),
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
v_{Q}=-\frac{\tau}{6}\frac{dv^{2}}{dT}(\nabla T)
\]

\end_inset

Now we know from the theory of EM and Newton that the velocity due to the
 uniform electric field (we haven't stated yet the origin of this field)
 will be
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
v_{E}=-\frac{eE\tau}{m}
\]

\end_inset

At equilibrium then, we can assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{E}+v_{Q}=0$
\end_inset

 (why?).
 This finally yields a linear relation between 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla T$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
E=\left(-\frac{1}{3e}\frac{d}{dT}\frac{mv^{2}}{2}\right)\nabla T=\left(-\frac{c_{v}}{3ne}\right)\nabla T=Q\nabla T;\, Q\equiv\left(-\frac{c_{v}}{3ne}\right)
\]

\end_inset

where we are not fully justified in the last substitution.
 Finally, we can use 
\begin_inset Formula $E=-\nabla V$
\end_inset

 to write 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
V=\alpha T;\,\alpha=-Q
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As a remark it must be mentioned that it is possible for 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{Q}$
\end_inset

 to be 
\begin_inset Formula $=0$
\end_inset

 while there is still heat flow in accordance with the temperature difference
 at equilibrium.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Experimental Verification
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
One might find it reasonable to think that the simplest way of measuring
 seeback effect would be to just stick in voltmeter probes to two points
 in a metal that're maintained at distinct temperatures.
 Reasonable as it sounds, there's a serious flaw; the voltmeter itself consists
 of metallic parts which will produce their own seeback effect due to the
 temperature difference at the probes.
 So then one may think it can be rectified by heating a metallic block at
 the middle and measuring the voltage difference at the equitemperature
 sides.
 Well, a little though reveals that this would be zero.
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Use 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta V=\alpha\Delta T$
\end_inset

; its trivial then
\end_layout

\end_inset

 However, the idea has merit.
 If we put two different metal blocks' edges in contact (it'll be both a
 thermal and electrical contact) and maintain it at temperture 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{C}$
\end_inset

 and measure voltage off of the open edges (with open edges of both metals
 maintained) at temperture 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{E}$
\end_inset

, we'll get a non-zero voltage (unless the metals have the same seeback
 cofficient).
 Let's calculate this potential difference.
 We assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{C}>T_{E}$
\end_inset

; 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta T=T_{c}-T_{E}>0$
\end_inset

, potential at the cold edge of metal one and two is 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{2}$
\end_inset

 respectively, and potential at the middle (common edge) is 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

, so that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{aligned} & V-V_{1}=\alpha_{1}\Delta T, & V-V_{2}=\alpha_{2}\Delta T\\
\implies & V_{2}-V_{1}=\left(\alpha_{2}-\alpha_{1}\right)\Delta T\\
\implies & \Delta V=\alpha\Delta T, & \alpha=\left(\alpha_{2}-\alpha_{1}\right),\,\Delta V=V_{2}-V_{1}
\end{aligned}
\]

\end_inset

This is a neat result.
 So all that I am now required to do is to keep 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta T$
\end_inset

 sufficiently large, so that I can measure 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta V$
\end_inset

 reliably using my voltmeter.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
The Setup
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
That setup should be then as described earlier.
 Well, almost because in our lab we have a slightly different setup.
 As shown in the diagram, across the circuit, we can write 
